Output modes — append, update, and complete.

The output mode controls which rows Spark writes to the sink, in each micro-batch — and it also controls whether the state store turns on.

Append is the default, and it is stateless. Only new rows go out, and no state store is used. Use it for simple projections, filters, and stateless transforms — and also for windowed aggregations, as long as they have a watermark, because then each closed window emits exactly once.

Update is stateful. The state store holds the running aggregates, per key, and update emits only the keys that changed in this batch.

Complete is also stateful. The state store holds the entire result table, and complete rewrites the whole sink, every single batch.

Spark enforces a few rules at query-start. Append, on a non-watermarked aggregation, is rejected — because Spark cannot know when a key is done, so it cannot safely emit it once. And both complete and update require an aggregation.

Now, why is complete dangerous at scale? Because it rewrites the entire result table on every trigger. Picture ten million keys, on a five-second trigger. Every five seconds, you are rewriting ten million rows. So production pipelines almost always use update instead, and let the downstream system — a Delta merge, or a database upsert — handle the merge.
